Leo sat beside her, not on the bed, but on the floor. "You're exaggerating," he said gently. "You're making it a hurricane when it's just a drizzle."

She blinked. "How do you know?"

"Because I remember when you helped me after my mom left. You brought me soup and stayed up all night listening. You didn't make it a hurricane; you just... showed up."

Maya's throat tightened. She hadn't thought about that. She'd been so focused on her own sadness, she'd forgotten how often love had been there, quiet and steady.

Leo smiled. "Love isn't a grand gesture, Maya. It's the quiet hum of being seen. Like this tea. Like me showing up."

She took the mug, the warmth spreading through her hands. Outside, the cloud drifted on, no longer a symbol of loneliness but a reminder that even clouds move, and so do feelings.

She leaned her head on his shoulder, the pillow forgotten. "Thank you," she said, her voice steady now.

Leo squeezed her hand. "Anytime."

